(like for anyone who's interested but maybe unaware, Sweden has had the most relaxed covid-policy in more or less the whole world (not even a singe lock - down) and is also one of the most privileged and free countries you can speak of...  A customer right before that,  who shared their belives went verbally savage on me and my coworkers for asking him to use sanitizer before touching unpackaged products..

Had a very tough practice today. Haven't done a practice in about 2 days because I've been feeling too tired. Finally felt a pull towards a practice this morning. Did good all the way up to the last side plank, where all the pain in my neck and pressure in the wrists really got to me. When the left and right sides of my body are not balanced, I get very unstable emotionally as well. I kind of collapsed physically and emotionally after the last side plank and went straight into childs pose and let myself quietly cry it out. The last pose I just sat with my legs slightly bent and trying to stretch my neck. It definitely sucked to cry and all the self-doubt most definitely wasn't fun. however, I was able to very quickly stop myself from blaming myself negatively for the "failure" and just started saying "it's okay" to myself instead of hating my body for not being able to do the toughest variations perfectly. 


Today's practice helped me understand that physical balance for me, is heavily linked to my emotional balance, and having a tough day on the mat is okay and necessary to learn when modifications are necessary.

Tues., 2/5/19: Today's session made me realize how disconnected I usually am to my core center, my belly. And this is the first time I've fully realized why. I realized that I don't like how fat my belly looks. But I immediately turned that expression towards something kinder and just asked myself, "Can I love my *soft* belly?" And I continued to looks at reasons for loving it the way that it is. It makes a great pillow for others to lay on. One day it may house another life form. Even if it doesn't look it, it has been strong enough to carry me through 22 days of ab challenges and yoga routines. And I did Whole30 to try and show it more love and give it the nutrients it needs to help support me better. It's true, one day I hope it will look as strong as it feels, but I think for me to get there, I have to start loving it the way that it is, so that I can connect more to it when things get tough. I hope that sharing this helps others in their self-love journey. Namaste c:

Yesss Adriene! Thank you! I feel the strongest I have felt in months (in mind and body.) I don't want my next comment to be about me... rather the amazing healing of yoga. I have some long-term health issues as a result of damage to the brain when I was younger. I don't really consider them as problems anymore. I have found ways to manage my memory, mood (mania, anxiety, depression, panic attacks) and mindset, through mindfulness, keeping a journal and enjoying the simple things life brings. These videos are a huge part of that healing. And I am so grateful to be on this journey. Life is a gift and I thank you with every part of my heart for helping me to honour that. I have accepted myself fully. I am observing my emotions without judgement; and that is so much easier than fully embodying them and allowing them to become me. I want to prove that no matter how down you may feel, no matter how oppressive something may seem, there is ALWAYS a way through it‚Ä¶ it is simply a case of knowing where to look. I love you and everyone who is showing up to the mat; because it's hard and we're doing it! There is a really incredible book by a Buddhist monk, Haemin Sunim, called "The Things You Can See Only When You Slow Down" and I would recommend it to everyone.
